http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: An attribute of a region vector layer
Atrribute of some region data sets
Attributes of a tabular dataset. Each attribute corresponds to a column in the table.
Point measures are point-like representations of fields. For example, point data sets denoting the locations of measured temperature values.
Field rasters are raster representations of continuous fields. For example, raster layers representing a terrain height (DTM).
A spatial dataset representing events
A generalized notion of a line in 2D and 3D
Attribute of some Line data set

A spatial dataset representing a spatial network. Note thate a network in the sense of a core concept is a quantified relation between objects. For example, the traffic flow between municipalities or between two intersections. Streets themselves can also be seen as objects if they do not encode such relations
A spatial attribute on nominal scale level
Events represented in terms of an attribute of a vector data set. For example, the magnitude of earthquakes represented as an attribute of a point data set.
A generalized geometry, including 2D and 3D extended regions. In 2D, this might be a Polygon.
A generalized notion of a point in 2D and 3D
A vector representation of a field. Can be a point or line measure, or a coverage, or a Patch
Dataset of amounts of objects
Superclass of of attribute types that characterize a geometric layer property
This attribute represents a quality of an event (core concept). For example, the duration.
A raster dataset where 0 is interpreted as boolean "false"
A region data set where spatial regions are tessellated (jointly covering and mutually non-overlapping) within a spatial extent
Intensive region attribute. An attribute that is independent from the size of its support region.

A vector layer attribute that satisfies a boolean expression and thus denotes the 'existence' of some attribute encoded phenomenon across space. Example is a layer of polygons of ''forest'' landuse or a layer of "parks".
An ordinal attribute that is plain/proper (not interval)
A spatial attribute on ordinal scale level
A dataset representing a field using (possibly irregular) patches of homogeneous values. For example, a landuse map or a soil map.
A single value of some quality
An attribute of a dataset that represents some quantified relation between other core concepts. For example a network is relation between objects.
A dataset which represents a field in terms patches of homogeneous values. Not necessarily tessellated

Extensive region attribute. Since attributes are extensive, their values increase with the size of their support regions. Zero size regions are zero then defined to be zero, which implies a ratio scale level.
An interval attribute that is plain/proper
This type of lattice has an extensive attribute. For example, a spatial dataset about the population number of municipalities
An attribute of an object line dataset
An attribute of a vector tessellation
An attribute that denotes counts of discrete entities (compare Chrisman 1998)
an attribute of a matrix. For example, distance in an origin-destination matrix.

Object vectors are vector representation of a set of objecs and their quality. For example, a point layer denoting points of Interest (POI) or buildings in a city together with their quality, e.g. the building height.
This is a vector data set which is tessellated (and no raster)
A representation of a field as a line of homogeneous values
An attribute of an object point dataset
Vector data sets are spatial data sets that are not raster
ofDataSet o hasElement o hasMeasure o valueOf
Attribute of some point data set
A network relation where the complete cross-product of an object domain forms the key. Examples would be origin-destination matrices.
An attribute that represents a (quantified) amount, which is a quantity defined by an arbitrary part of space. This can be either an amount of objects or an amount of some field.
An interval scaled attribute
A lattice is a spatial tessellation that represents objects and their qualities. For example, a set of municipalities with average income.
A dataset that represents some quantified realtionb between other concepts. For example, a network (being a relation between objects).
This is a spatial attribute which denotes a bounded phenomenon. Can be either a object vector or an existence raster
A dataset of objects which tesselate space and contain statistical summaries. For example, the municipalities of the Netherlands
Dataset with vector regions as geometry
A raster data set is a special kind of tessellation, where regions are regular squares.
Vector regions that are not tessellated
A raster dataset where  NoData is interpreted as boolean "false".
A ratio attribute that is plain/proper
Boolean attributes are spatial attributes within the range of True/False. They are special types of (bi)nominal attributes
A dataset representing a field by homogeneous values using raster cells
A dataset representing tracks, i.e. point wise events (fixes) of the trajectory of some objects.
Spatial attribute on ratio scale level
Superclass of all core concept qualities.
A nominal attribute that is plain/proper (not ordinal or boolean)
A type for a spatial track. A spatial track is a vector representation of "fix" events of some moving object. For example, a GPS track of points of a person moving.
An attribute of a vector region layer that is not a tessellation
An attribute that represents the quality of an object (core concept)

This ontology pattern describes geodata types representing core concepts of spatial information (Kuhn 2012) we well as further semantic attribute distinctions relevant for geocomputation and geo-analysis.
ofDataSet o hasElement o hasSupport o valueOf
Attribute of some Raster
A dataset where each geometry denotes an amount of objects
A data set which represents a core concept of spatial information. The attributes of this dataset are assumed to be of corresponding types.
A spatial dataset representing a field
Contour layers are coverages that denote intervals of the reprepresented continuous field. For example, temperature intervals, represented as regions bounded by isolines of a temperature field.
A dataset representing a field using contours, which denote the boundaries of value intervals. For example, a terrain contour map.
Attribute of some vector data set
An attribute of some dataset representing homogeneous patches of a field as regions.
A dataset representing a field in terms of point-wise measures. For example, temperature sensor measurements.
Coverages are tessellated layers that represent a continuous field. For example, landuse polygons.
An attribute of a tesselation data set

This attribute represents the quality of a network edge. Note that spatial networks (as core concepts) are regarded as quantified relations between objects. So O-IRA-O would be an intensive quality measured between two objects, such as their distance from each other.
Existence rasters are rasters representing boolean fields (fields denoting whether something is present at a cell location or not).
Linear representations of fields. Examples are isoline maps
A raster data set where each cell represents an amount of objects
An attribute which represents the quality of a field (core concept). This implies that the spatial data items in this data set are self-similar (their parts have the same attribute)
A spatial data set representing objects
